THREE people were killed during a shooting incident at Joburg Taxi Rank in Philippi, Cape Town on Saturday. Four suspects arrived at the rank and allegedly opened fire without saying a word. Two men – a taxi owner and a mechanic – died at the scene, while the third victim passed away later in hospital. if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Nosisa Ntantiso (39) was on her way to the mall when the shooting happened. “I was waiting for a taxi to the mall when I heard gunshots.“I hid next to a container. I did not look to see who was shooting for fear of being hit by a stray bullet,” Nosisa said. Aonther resident, Busisiwe Veco (43), said she felt sorry for the families, especially the relatives of the mechanic.“I think the mechanic was caught in the crossfire because he did not own a taxi. I’m not sure if this had anything to do with taxi people.”Another resident said it would have been worse if the incident happened during the week.“Imagine if the shooting happened during the week. “Our kids would have been caught in the crossfire because they use taxis to school,” the mum said.Western Cape police spokesman Captain Frederick van Wyk said three men aged 35, 42 and 43 were fatally shot at the taxi rank.“Two died at the scene and the third one was taken to a nearby hospital but died on arrival. “The motive for the shooting is unknown. “A triple murder case has been registered for investigation,” said Van Wyk.Anyone with information about the incident should call 08600 10111.